"1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Youth Sport Trust believes that every young person has the right to high quality physical education (PE) and school sport. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We believe that PE should provide the physical literacy and learning which forms the basis of participation </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">in school sport, and </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">the foundation of a healthy, active lifestyle. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">e believe it is particularly important that all girls are given positive experiences of PE and school sport,</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> and through both are supported to develop positive body image, and</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> empowered to build lifelong invo</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">lvement in sport and physical</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> activity</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Youth Sport Trust is concerned that a recent study published in the British Medical Journal, which found that</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> just</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> 38% of 7 year-old girls are achieving the recommended daily amount of physical activity, compar</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ed to 63% of boys.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> In addition, t</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">here continues to be an alarming ‘drop-off’ in participation rates amongst girls when they enter secondary school. The last PE and School Sport Survey, conducted in 2010, found that 68% of Year 6 girls took part in at leas</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">t three hours of high quality PE and school sport. However, by year 13 this figure had fallen to just 15%. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Research also shows that just 10% of girls aged 14 are achieving the Chief Medical Officer’s recommended physical activity level of 60 minutes per </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">day</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Our commitment to engaging girls in school sport and PE</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Since our inception in 1995, the Youth Sport Trust has been committed to involving all girls in PE, sport and physical activity. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We have</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> been working with schools to find ways of increasing gi</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">rls</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> participation in PE and sport for many years. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">For example:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In 1998, following extensive research, Nike and the Youth Sport Trust established the Nike Girls in Sport Programme, which equipped PE teachers from 2,271 secondary schools with skills and </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ideas to develop ‘girl friendly’ PE</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In 2006 we built on this developing the Norwich Union Girls Active initiative, empowering teenage girls to enjoy PE and sport through greater choice and student voice. This produced significant changes in attitude </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">towards participation in both PE and after school sport</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Despite these successes and excellent practice in some schools, more recent research</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub"> </span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub"> </span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">found that while PE and school sport meets the needs of ‘sporty’ girls, it often remains unattractive to less</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> active girls.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Youth Sport Trust’s Girls PE and Sport Innovation Project, which is currently completing its pilot phase, has built on best practice and the results of the research to help teachers make PE and sport more relevant to girls, and empower </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">girls through leadership and marketing to increase their own participation, develop as role models and ‘sell’ PE and sport to other girls.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Looking at current interventions, we are del</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ghted to be delivering a number of programmes, in partnership with Gov</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ernment, which aim to give girls access to high quality PE and school sport. The School Games, which the Youth Sport Trust delivers in partnership with the Department for Culture, Media and Sport seeks to give all young people the chance to take part in hi</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">gh-quality, competitive school sport. We are delighted that, to date, over 17,500 schools have signed up to the programme. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Youth Sport Trust also works with the </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Department of Health to deliver Change 4 Life Sports Clubs. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Clubs are aimed at ‘less </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">active’ young people in both primary and secondary schools, and aim to encourage them to do more physical activity and engage in sport. The Youth Sport Trust has established over 8,500 clubs in schools around the country and the programme has involved over</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> 150,000 children and young people </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">in sport and physical activity.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In Scotland, the Youth Sport Trust delivers the Fit for Girls programme in partnership wi</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">th</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">sport</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">scotland</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">. Since the programme began four years ago, evidence shows that Fit for Girls has </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">supported and encouraged good practice within schools across Scotland</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Fit</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> for Girls promotes physical activity among girls aged 11-16, with a particular focus on those who are likely to be least active. The programme is delivered through secondary schools</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> and provides training for PE teachers and school sport professionals. It equ</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ips them with the knowledge, too</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ls and skills they need to plan and implement positive PE and physical activity experiences for girls in secondary school settings. The programme f</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ocuses on the need to consult with girls and facilitate their input in the PE, sport and physical activity which they are involved. It is based on research w</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">hich shows that consulting with girls in this </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">w</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ay leads to them enjoying more positive sporting exp</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">erienc</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">es. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Since Fit for Girls was launched in 2008, 344 mainstream schools, and </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">15 A</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">dditional Support Needs</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">schools have engaged with the programme, with 32 local authorities having committed to its delivery. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Elsewhere, t</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">hrough our Girls PE and Sport Innovation project, the Youth Sport Trust is </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">piloting work</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> with 21 schools around the country to help them better engage 11-14 year old girls in PE and sport, and drive up participation rates. The project provides schools with</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">training, resources and ongoing support to help them review their PE and sport culture and practices to ensure they are relevant and attractive to girls.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">It utilises branding and peer to peer marketing techniques to support and encourage girls to be activ</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">e, and to make physical activity a central part of their identity. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">To date, the Girls’ Innovation proje</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ct has reached over 1,200 girls, with schools involved reporti</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ng that it has had an extremely </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">positive impact. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Youth Sport Trust is currently working</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> to secure national roll out of the programme. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Challenges in enhancing girls</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">’</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> participation in PE and school sport</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Through our work with schools and teachers around the country, the Youth Sport Trust is </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">aware of many instances of outstanding PE and school sport provision that effectively engages </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">girls in both primary and secondary schools. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">However, </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">through our bespoke </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">esearch</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">, and our knowledge of the delivery of PE and school sport on the ground,</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Youth Sport Trust has f</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ound that there are </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">a number of</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> persiste</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">nt issues affecting girls</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> engagement in PE and school sport. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Physical Literacy: </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Youth Sport Trust believes it is i</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">mperative that all children are given the basic physi</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">cal literacy skills they need to build life-long participation in sport and physical activity. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Following the removal of central funding for School Sport Partnerships in October 2010, </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">the Youth Sport Trust believes that there was a significant reduction in </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">the capacity of many primary schools to deliver high quality PE an</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">d school sport to their pupils. The vast majority of primary schools have no specialist PE provision, and around half of all primary school teachers receive only 10 hours or less of speciali</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">st PE training. As a result, Youth Sport Trust research shows that many lack the confidence and competence to deliver the subject properly,</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> while </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Ofsted</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> recent report into PE found that some primary school teachers “lack the specialist knowledge needed to teach PE well”</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Youth Sport Trust therefore welcomes the Government’s decision, announced earlier this year, to invest £150 million in primary scho</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ol sport each of the next two years, and believe this money has the potential to significantly enhance provision at primary school level. We are particularly pleased that the investment will be </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">full ring-fenced. </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In order for its impact to be maximised, t</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">he Youth Sport Trust believe it is imperative that schools are given support and direction on how best deploy this new investment, and should be actively encouraged to cooperate and share resources in order to achieve the best possible outcomes for their </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">upils. We are currently working with </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">a range of government department and agencies </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">to ensure schools get the support and direction they need.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In addition, as mentioned above, recent research that many primary-age girls are not undertaking sufficient amou</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">nts of physical activity. The Youth Sport Trust therefore believes that primary schools should</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> be encouraged to ensure their </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">PE and school sport provision engages girls effectively</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> and, crucially, that girl’s participation in both is valued to the same extent as boys. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Content of PE and school sport provision: </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Youth Sport Trust’s research shows that in many schools the content of PE and school sport provision is often unappeali</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ng to those girls who are less active and don’t consider themselves to fit </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">the traditional ‘sporty’ stereotype</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> T</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">his problem can lead to girls not engaging in PE at all, or doing the ‘bare minimum’ of activity to get through lessons. The positive benefits</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> of physical activity of least two hours a week are therefore often lost for this group because their activity levels are not high in curriculum PE lessons. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Research</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> from the Women</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">’s Sport and Fitness Foundation (in which the Youth Sport Trust was a lead p</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">artner)</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> submitted to the Education Select Committee’s inquiry into school sport, reported that 51% of </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">secondary school-age </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">girls are currently being put off by their expe</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">riences of PE and school sport.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Youth Sport Trust therefore believes that it is imperative that schools are encouraged and supported to offer a diverse range of sporting activities that appeal to all groups of girls, and offer them desirable participation experiences. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The manner in w</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">hich PE is delivered</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> also needs to be catered to girls</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> preferences. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">We believe that the programme of study for PE contained within the National Curriculum should outline the need for schools to offer a wide range of sporting activities. We are</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> therefore</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> concerned that the recently published final draft of the revised National Curriculum contains reference to named sports (such as hockey, netball or football)</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">. The Youth Sport Trust believes</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> these references could encourage schools to offer only ‘tradition</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">al’ sports and thus alienate many of their female pupils, and would welcome their removal from the National Curriculum. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="3" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Relevance of physical activity to girls’ lives</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">m</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">arketing </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">of PE and school sport to girls)</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">: </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Youth Sport Trust has found that m</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">any </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">girls</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">, particularly those of secondary school age,</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> do not see the relevance of physical activity to t</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">heir lives. They don’t regard PE and school sport</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> as a ‘natural’ part of their lifestyle, and don’t recognise the wider benefits of being active. </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Through</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> our research into girls’ attitudes, the Youth Sport Trust</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> has found that many girls do not</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> enjoy sport ‘for s</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">port’s sake’.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> We believe that one of the key</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">s to making PE </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">sport a priority for those girls </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">to ensure that both are relevant to girls’ </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">interests. For example, PE with a clearl</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">y articulated purpose such as</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> develop</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ing confidence, enhancing body image, improving health or preparing</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> for a set-piece performance</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> or charity fundraising event</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">, is much more likely to engage girls effectively. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In t</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">his sense these outcomes should not be seen as by-products of PE and school sport, but as planned outcomes of both. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Crucially, the Youth Sport Trust be</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">lieves that, in order to </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">effectively ‘market’</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> PE and school sport to all girls, schools need to unders</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">tand what motivates their female pupils to take part in PE, and to be physically active. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">As mentioned above, t</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">hrough our </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Girls PE and Sport Innovation project</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">, the Youth Sport Trust is working with 21 schools around the country to help them</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> better engage </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">11-14 year old girls in PE and sport, and</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> drive up participation rates. The project provides schools with training, res</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ources and ongoing support to help them review their PE and sport culture and</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> develop innovative</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> practices to ensure they </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">are relevant and attractive to girls. A key part of this process is encouraging schools to establish Girls Leadership and Marketing groups (or </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">GLAMS), made up of a cross-section of female pupils, which establish girls’ motivations, and influence delivery w</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ithin the school. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Fit for Girls programme, mentioned above a</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">nd</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> delivered in </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">partnership with </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">sport</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">scotland</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">has</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> been highly successful</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">in encouraging</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> PE staff to carry out consultation </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">with their female pupils, with 98.8% </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">of PE staff who have taken </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">part</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> in the programme reporting that they undertook such a consultation. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Meanwhile, 60% of PE staff reported that Fit for Girls had helped to increase girls' participation in PE, sport and physical activity. In particular, those who were involved in Fit fo</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">r Girls noted that it helped to remove barriers to girls taking part in PE and sport and increase their confidence and enthusiasm for the subject.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Fit for Girls </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">has start</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ed to create a culture change in</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> PE, physical activity and sport engagement for adole</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">scent girls in schools. Building on this learning, Fit for Girls is now offering schools the opportunity to engage with a Fit for Girls trainer in a bespoke 1:1 </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">approach in order t</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">o allow discussions and solutions to be individually tailored to meet school</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> needs.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Youth Sport Trust </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">would welcome direction from government for</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> all secondary schools to consult with their </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">female </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">pupils in this way. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="4" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Positive role models</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">: </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Youth Sport Trust believes it is imperative that girls are exposed to positive, </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">active role models to whom they can aspire. Through programmes such as Sky Sports Living for Sport, which uses athlete mentors to help secondary school pupils engage with their education, the Y</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">outh Sport Trust has seen first-</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">hand </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">positive effect of sportin</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">g role models on young people. The Youth Sport Trust would welcome a recommendation from the </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Committee for wider exposure for</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> positive, active female role models in the mainstream media. </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In addition the Youth Sport Trust believes that schools should be encouraged to develop their own female sporting role models. With a lack of positive role models in the media, older girls in school can serve as strong role models for younger girls, demons</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">trating the realistic possibilities of what they can achieve. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">A crucial element of the Youth Sport Trust’s Girls PE and Innovation project, is that the ‘GLAMS’ mentioned above also act as role models to younger girls and help to ‘sell’ participation in PE </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">and school sport. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="5" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Competitive School Sport</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">: </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The Youth Sport Trust recognises the Government’s commitment to driving the take-up of competitive sport in schools. Participation in competitive sport is a key part of any child’s sporting journey, and allows </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">young people to build key life skills such as teamwork, determination and leadership. However, we believe that any focus on competition should not be at the cost of allowing all young people to participate fully in PE and school sport, including those who </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">are less inclined to take part in competitive activities. </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Research shows that boys are more likely than girls to prefer school sport or physical activity to be competitive</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> In order to engage all young people, including girls, in competition, it is imperative that sporting formats are fully inclusive, and the wider benefits of taking part are emphasised to young people and school sport practitioners. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In addition, while som</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">e girls find traditional, confrontational, models of competition off-putting, research shows they are more likely to engage in personal or group challenge activities</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">. The Youth Sport Trust therefore believes that government and practitioners should employ</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> a diverse approach which values different forms of competition equally. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Griffiths LJ, Cortina-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Borja</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> M, Sera F, et al </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">How active are our children? Findings from the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Millenium</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Cohort Study</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">BMJ Open </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">(2013)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Health Behaviour in School Aged Children (2011) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">England National Report &amp; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Department of Health (2011) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Physical Activity Guidelines for children and young people </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">(2011)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">O’Donovan, T. And Kay, T. (2006) Girls in Sport. Monitoring and Evaluating: Final Report</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family: